\begin_layout Chapter
Model of Solution System
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "chpt:models"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Computing models of solvents are broadly divided into two types: those treating
 the solvent as a continuous medium (implicit models) and those describing
 the individual solvent molecules (explicit models).
 In the continuum model, the solvent is characterized by the dielectric
 constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 and contains an artificially shaped cavity.
 The explicit models can have more specific microscopic scales.
 Within the scope of classical mechanics, the most detailed (and thus the
 most expensive) methods involve flexible and polarizable explicit models,
 while in computational chemistry, less detailed models often have wider
 usage (for example, the proteins are treated in the unity of residues).
 As the theory of liquids was initially established for spherical atom-like
 solvent particles, the model adopted by such a theory is a rigid entity
 carrying distributed point charges, characterized by their position and
 orientation, i.e.
 there is no internal movement considered.
 This approximation has been proven reasonable 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Gray-Gubbins"

\end_inset

.
 There also exist models in which the scale lies somewhere between the implicit
 and explicit models; for example, so-called coarse-grained models 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "hadley_coarse-grained_2012"

\end_inset

, which gather groups of atoms into a single interaction site.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we will give a brief introduction of the implicit model
 in order to facilitate later discussion on solvation free energy corrections.
 We will then focus on the rigid solvent models and discuss the limits of
 such approximations.
 The flexible and polarizable models will also be briefly mentioned.
 
\end_layout

