\begin_layout Standard
The solvation Gibbs free energy according to this model is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta G_{\mathrm{solvation}}=\Delta G_{\mathrm{cavity}}+\Delta G_{\mathrm{dispersion}}+\Delta G_{\mathrm{elec}}\label{eq:Continuum-mod}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta G_{\mathrm{cavity}}>0$
\end_inset

 is the energy needed to create a hole in the medium, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta G_{\mathrm{dispersion}}$
\end_inset

 is the dispersion interaction, which is roughly the van der Waals energy
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta G_{\mathrm{vdW}}<0$
\end_inset

 between the solvent and solute.
 In principle, there may also be a repulsive component, and the dispersion
 term is sometimes denoted dispersion/repulsion.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta G_{\mathrm{elec}}<0$
\end_inset

 is the contribution of electrostatic interactions, introduced by electric
 charge distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 which polarizes the medium, and the action back of the medium on the molecule
 (reaction field).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The initial two terms in eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Continuum-mod"

\end_inset

) are linked to the configuration of the first solvation shell (cavity).
 The definition of cavity varies from the simplest sphere or ellipsoid to
 the ensemble of atomic surfaces defined by the van der Waals radii in the
 solute.
 It is somewhat reasonable to consider the cavity area as proportional to
 the number of solvent molecules in the first solvation shell.
 This number can be calculated as the area passing through the middle region
 of first shell solvent.
 This area, named the solvent-accessible surface area (SASA) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "SAS_1,SAS_2"

\end_inset

, can be calculated by adding the radius of the probe solvent ball on the
 solvent excluded surface area (figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:sasa"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

