\begin_layout Subsection
Poisson-Boltzmann methods
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Poisson–Boltzmann-methods"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Poisson-Boltzmann equation (PBE) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "holst_1994_poisson"

\end_inset

 makes it possible to calculate the position-dependent electrostatic potential
 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\mathrm{elec}}(\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset

 in the continuum model, such that the electrostatic component of the free
 energy can be written as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta G_{\mathrm{elec}}=\frac{1}{2}\int\mathrm{d}\mathbf{r}\rho_{q}(\mathbf{r})V_{\mathrm{elec}}(\mathbf{r})
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{q}$
\end_inset

 is the charge distribution of the solute.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Maxwell-Gauss equation in SI units convention gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\nabla\cdot D(\mathbf{r})=\dfrac{\rho_{q}(\mathbf{r})}{\varepsilon_{0}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $D(\mathbf{r})=\varepsilon_{0}E(\mathbf{r})+P(\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset

 is the electric displacement field, 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset

 is the system polarization, 
\begin_inset Formula $E(\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset

 the electric field, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{0}$
\end_inset

 the vacuum permittivity.
 
\begin_inset Formula $D(\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset

 can also be expressed in terms of the position-dependent dielectric constant
 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon(\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $D(\mathbf{r})=\varepsilon(\mathbf{r})E(\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset

, which thus gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\nabla\cdot\varepsilon(\mathbf{r})E(\mathbf{r})=\dfrac{\rho_{q}(\mathbf{r})}{\varepsilon_{0}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

or in terms of electrostatic potential:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\nabla\cdot\left[\varepsilon(\mathbf{r})\nabla V_{\mathrm{elec}}(\mathbf{r})\right]=-\dfrac{\rho_{q}(\mathbf{r})}{\varepsilon_{0}}\label{eq:poisson}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This second-order differential equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:poisson"

\end_inset

) is called the Poisson equation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This equation cannot be solved analytically for complex geometries (such
 as a protein).
 Therefore it is done numerically using appropriate methods; for example,
 mentioned in the article of Roux and Simonson 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "roux_implicit_1999"

\end_inset

 or Holst 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "holst_1994_poisson"

\end_inset

.
 A density functional approach based on the minimization of the polarization
 density can also be used to solve this equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Marchi_2001,Levy_2005"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the solvent is ionic, the Poisson equation can be modified by taking
 into account a (thermal) Boltzmann distribution of ions in the solvent,
 i.e.,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho_{\mathrm{tot}}(\mathbf{r})=\rho_{q}(\mathbf{r})-2qn_{\mathrm{ion}}\sinh(\frac{q}{k_{\mathrm{B}}T}V_{\mathrm{elec}}(\mathbf{r}))
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for a salt composed of ions of charge 
\begin_inset Formula $+\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $-\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

 and of density 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\mathrm{ion}}$
\end_inset

.
 Replacing in eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:poisson"

\end_inset

) leads to the Poisson-Boltzmann Equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\nabla\cdot(\varepsilon(\mathbf{r})\nabla V_{\mathrm{elec}}(\mathbf{r}))-\dfrac{2qn_{\mathrm{ion}}}{\varepsilon_{0}}\sinh\left(\dfrac{qV_{\mathrm{elec}}(\mathbf{r})}{k_{\mathrm{B}}T}\right)=-\dfrac{\rho(\mathbf{r})}{\varepsilon_{0}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Born / Onsager / Generalized Born models
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Born-/-Onsager"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For simple geometries, the Poisson equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:poisson"

\end_inset

) can be solved analytically.
 The simplest model is a spherical cavity.
 For a net charge 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 in a cavity of radius 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

, the electrostatic free energy of a medium with a dielectric constant of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 is given by the Born formula:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta G_{\mathrm{elec}}(q)=-\dfrac{1}{8\pi\varepsilon_{0}}\left(1-\frac{1}{\varepsilon}\right)\frac{q^{2}}{2a}\label{eq:born_model}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Other similar models include the Onsager model, in which a point dipole
 (characterized by the dipole moment 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

) is put in a spherical cavity.
 The Kirkwood model refers to a general multipole expansion in a spherical
 cavity, while the Kirkwood-Westheimer model arises for an ellipsoidal cavity.
 Those simplified models are not fully able to predict the solvent behavior
 in many realistic cases 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Jensen"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The generalized Born (GB) model is an empirical model based on the superposition
 of several net charges in spherical cavities as the Born model describes,
 with a similar formula:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta G_{\mathrm{elec}}=-\dfrac{1}{8\pi\varepsilon_{0}}\left(1-\frac{1}{\varepsilon}\right)\sum_{i}\sum_{j}\frac{q_{i}q_{j}}{f_{ij}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{ij}$
\end_inset

 depends on the internuclear distance 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{ij}$
\end_inset

 between the centers of atoms 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 and on the Born radii for each pair of atoms 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{j}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f_{ij}=\sqrt{r_{ij}^{2}-a_{i}a_{j}\exp\left(\frac{r_{ij}^{2}}{4a_{i}a_{j}}\right)}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The key (empirical) point is to be able to attribute an effective Born radius
 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}$
\end_inset

 to each atom inside the complex, non-spherical cavity formed by the solute.
 Once this is accomplished, the GB model provides a very fast method, with
 an overall accuracy comparable to that of Poisson-Boltzmann calculations.
 That makes it widely used in computational structural biology to perform
 structure optimization and molecular dynamics simulations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Model potential of explicit molecules
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:rigid-model-potential"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The model potential frequently used in the theory of liquids is a classical,
 rigid, pairwise additive model 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Hensen-McDonald,Gray-Gubbins"

\end_inset

.
 It is based on three assumptions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Firstly, the quantum effects should be ignored.
 It is assumed that the rotational and transitional motion of solvent particles
 are continuous and classical, which means the separation of both transitional
 and rotational states are largely inferior of 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{\mathrm{B}}T$
\end_inset

.
 For light molecules, that is not always convincing.
 Some molecules containing hydrogen (e.
 g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{H_{2}O}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{NH_{3}}$
\end_inset

, and particularly 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{H_{2}}$
\end_inset

) exhibit obvious quantum effects at low temperature in the liquid state.
 Gaseous 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{H_{2}O}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{NH_{3}}$
\end_inset

 also need quantum effect corrections.
 However, for the liquid of most interest to us, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{H_{2}O}$
\end_inset

 at room temperature, the contribution of this effect is small enough to
 be neglected.
 And obviously, there should not be any chemical interaction of the solvent
 with the solute.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Secondly,
\begin_inset Marginal
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Compared to atomic models that only depend on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}^{N}$
\end_inset

, the angular correlations can give influence on both structural and thermodynam
ic proprieties.
 That is why our theory is extended to linear case, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\Omega}\equiv(\Theta,\Phi)$
\end_inset

, then molecular case, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\Omega}\equiv(\Theta,\Phi,\Psi)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 the intramolecular movement (vibration and internal rotation) should be
 either independent of transitional and rotational movement or absent.
 This rigid molecule approximation assumes that the intermolecular potential
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{U}(\mathbf{r}^{N},\mathbf{\Omega}^{N})$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 particles only depends on the positions of the 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 molecular centers 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}^{N}\equiv(\mathbf{r}_{1},\mathbf{r}_{2},\ldots,\mathbf{r}_{N})$
\end_inset

 and on their orientations 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\Omega}^{N}\equiv(\mathbf{\Omega}_{1},\mathbf{\Omega}_{2},\cdots,\mathbf{\Omega}_{N})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\Omega}\equiv(\Theta,\Phi,\Psi)$
\end_inset

 represents the Euler angles (figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Euler-angles"

\end_inset

).
 The natural choice for the molecular center is the center of mass.
 This is, however, arbitrary if only equilibrium properties are considered.
