\begin_layout Standard
The rigid approximation is quite realistic for molecules in which the separation
 of vibrational states largely exceeds 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{\mathrm{B}}T$
\end_inset

, implying that the molecule stays in its ground vibrational state.
 This is the case for many small solvent molecules such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{N_{2}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{CO_{2}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{C_{6}H_{6}}$
\end_inset

, and indeed for the bending and stretching modes of water.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Finally, the intermolecular forces have to be assumed as pairwise additive:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{U}(\mathbf{r}^{N},\mathbf{\Omega}^{N})=\frac{1}{2}\sum_{i\neq j}u(\mathbf{r}_{ij},\mathbf{\Omega_{i}},\mathbf{\Omega_{j}})=\sum_{i<j}u(\mathbf{r}_{ij},\mathbf{\Omega_{i}},\mathbf{\Omega_{j}})\label{eq:pair-potential}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This means that the model potential only depends on the intermolecular separatio
n 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}$
\end_inset

 and on the molecular orientations 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\Omega}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\Omega}_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 This approximation is quasi-exact for low density gases, where the contribution
 of the three and more body terms decreases rapidly.
 But for dense fluids, in most of the cases the multi-body potential cannot
 be ignored.
 The complete model potential with higher-order corrections can be written
 in the form of
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{U}(\mathbf{r}^{N},\mathbf{\Omega}^{N})=\sum_{i<j}u(ij)+\sum_{i<j<k}u(ijk)+\sum_{i<j<k<l}u(ijkl)+...
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $u(ij)=u(\mathbf{r}_{ij},\mathbf{\Omega_{i}},\mathbf{\Omega_{j}})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u(ijk)=u(\mathbf{r}_{ij},\mathbf{r}_{jk},\mathbf{r}_{ki},\mathbf{\Omega_{i}},\mathbf{\Omega_{j}},\mathbf{\Omega_{k}})$
\end_inset

, etc.
 The omission of the three-body and higher-order terms can cause error,
 for example, in surface tension and surface energy calculation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Miyazaki_1975"

\end_inset

.
 However the higher-order terms are often accounted for by an effective
 pair potential (measured by experiments or calculated by simulations),
 which reduces considerably the computational cost for simulations, or the
 degree of theory needed.
 Such models are presented below going from simple to molecular liquids.
 For the molecular solvent considered in this thesis, water, most publications
 have stayed at this two-body level of description.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Interaction of spherical particle
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The simplest model of a fluid is the hard sphere model.
 With 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 the hard-sphere diameter, the pair potential is defined as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
u(r)=\begin{cases}
\infty & r<d\\
0 & r>d
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This model is indeed a fundamental reference model in statistical mechanics,
 and it can represent some physical systems, such as neutral colloidal suspensio
ns 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Cohen1998251"

\end_inset

.
 However, the absence of attractive force, which precludes the existence
 of a liquid-gas transition, makes it too simple for realistic fluids.
 More realistic neutral particle models, like the Lenard-Jones (LJ) model,
 exhibit a potential energy curve that has the same shape as the real interactio
n of rare gas, as shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:LJ-pair-potential"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

