LJ pair potential
\end_layout

\end_inset

LJ pair potential.
 The plot gives the potential energy 
\begin_inset Formula $u(r)$
\end_inset

 versus internuclear distance 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 of two particles.
 At large distances, both attractive and repulsive interactions are small.
 As the distance between the atoms decreases, the attractive electron-proton
 interactions dominate, and the energy of the system decreases.
 At the observed bond distance, the repulsive electron-electron and proton-proto
n interactions just balance the attractive interactions, preventing a further
 decrease in the internuclear distance.
 At very short internuclear distances, the repulsive interactions dominate,
 making the system less stable than the isolated atoms.
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:LJ-pair-potential"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Lennard-Jones (LJ) interaction gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
u_{LJ}(r)=4\varepsilon\left[\left(\frac{\sigma}{r}\right)^{12}-\left(\frac{\sigma}{r}\right)^{6}\right]
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is the distance from centre to centre, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is the collision diameter or the particles separation where 
\begin_inset Formula $u(r)=0$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 is the well depth of the potential (of unity of energy).
 The well minimum occurs at 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\min}=2^{1/6}\sigma$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u(r_{\min})=-\epsilon$
\end_inset

.
 The parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 can be extracted from experiments.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Theoretically, all terms in the multipole series represent attractive contributi
ons to the potential.
 The leading term, varying as 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{-6}$
\end_inset

, describes the quantum dipole-dipole interaction.
 Higher-order terms represent dipole-quadrupole (
\begin_inset Formula $r^{-8}$
\end_inset

), quadrupole-quadrupole (
\begin_inset Formula $r^{-10}$
\end_inset

) interactions, and so on, but these are negligible compared to 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{-6}$
\end_inset

.
 The short-range interaction is difficult to define properly, and for the
 sake of simplicity and numerical efficiency, it is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{-12}$
\end_inset

 in the LJ model.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the spherical particles are charged (as in molten salts), the electrostatic
 interaction between them is described by the Coulomb point charge interaction:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
u_{\mathrm{Coul}}(r)=\frac{q_{1}q_{2}}{4\pi\varepsilon_{0}r}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For such charged simple fluids, the overall pair 
\begin_inset Formula $u(r)$
\end_inset

 is a sum of LJ and Coulomb interactions.
 Such decomposition can be extended to molecular fluids in terms of site-site
 interactions, which are discussed in the following section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Site-site interactions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Indeed, a spherical description of interactions is not sufficient to fully
 describe molecular fluids.
 The site-site model is a further extension of atomic models, in which the
 solvent molecule is represented by a set of discrete interaction sites.
 The total potential energy is a sum of spherical interaction potentials:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
u(1,2)=\sum_{\alpha}\sum_{\beta}u_{\alpha\beta}(\left|\mathbf{r}_{2\beta}-\mathbf{r}_{1\alpha}\right|)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}_{is}$
\end_inset

 is the coordinates of site 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 in molecule 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\alpha\beta}(r)$
\end_inset

 the interatomic potential energy of pairs of sites 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

, as discussed above.
 More specifically, it is generally decomposed into a Lennard-Jones and
 a Coulombic contribution:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
u(1,2)=\sum_{\alpha}\sum_{\beta}\left\{ 4\epsilon_{\alpha\beta}\left[\left(\frac{\sigma_{\alpha\beta}}{r_{12}^{\alpha\beta}}\right)^{12}-\left(\frac{\sigma_{\alpha\beta}}{r_{12}^{\alpha\beta}}\right)^{6}\right]\:+\frac{1}{4\pi\varepsilon_{0}}\frac{q_{\alpha}q_{\beta}}{r_{12}^{\alpha\beta}}\right\} 
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{12}^{\alpha\beta}=\left|\mathbf{r}_{2\beta}-\mathbf{r}_{1\alpha}\right|$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{\alpha\beta}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\alpha\beta}$
\end_inset

 are the site-site LJ parameters and 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 the partial charge on each site.
 This model is the most commonly adopted, and it will be so in this thesis
 for the calculation of external free energy functional.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Multipole and spherical harmonic expansion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To obtain fewer terms in the calculation, the model potential can be presented
 in convergent series via multipole or spherical harmonic expansion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For polar liquids, the dipole-dipole interaction should be mainly taken
 into account.
 Thus the model considers dipole-dipole interactions in addition to a sphericall
y symmetric Lennard-Jones-like potential:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
u(1,2)=u_{0}(r)-\boldsymbol{\mu}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{T}(\mathbf{r})\cdot\boldsymbol{\mu}_{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}$
\end_inset

 is the vector separation of the molecular centers, 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{0}(r)$
\end_inset

 is the spherically symmetric term discussed above, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\mu}_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the dipole moment vector of particle 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{T}(\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset

 is the dipole-dipole interaction tensor:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
T(\mathbf{r})=\nabla^{2}\left(\dfrac{1}{r}\right)=3\mathbf{r}\mathbf{r}/r^{5}-\mathbf{I}/r^{3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{I}$
\end_inset

 is the unit tensor.
 Note that this model can be made more realistic by including higher-order
 electrostatic interactions, such as dipole-quadrupole, quadrupole-quadrupole,
 etc.
 Such a systematic multipolar approach has been proposed for water 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Chowdhuri_2006"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Alternatively, the intermolecular potential can be expanded onto rotational
 invariants in the form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
u(\mathbf{r}_{12},\mathbf{\Omega}_{1},\mathbf{\Omega}_{2})=\sum_{mnl\mu\nu}u_{\mu\nu}^{mnl}(r_{12})\Phi_{\mu\nu}^{mnl}(\hat{\mathbf{r}}_{12},\mathbf{\Omega}_{1},\mathbf{\Omega}_{2})
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the angular basis functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{\mu\nu}^{mnl}(\hat{\mathbf{r}}_{12},\mathbf{\Omega}_{1},\mathbf{\Omega}_{2})$
\end_inset

 can be expressed in terms of generalized spherical harmonics (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
acs{GSH}
\end_layout

\end_inset

s) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Gray-Gubbins"

\end_inset

.
 A detailed description of rotational invariant transform is in appendix
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chpt:rotational-invariant-expansion"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

